<div class="post">
<div class="inner" id="msg_1038063"><span style="font-size: 14pt;" class="bbc_size">神的本质The Nature of the Divine</span><br>当然，不管GM用什么游戏系统来呈现新王国，都需要呈现神的能力、力量和缺点。这里有一些关于它们的一般思想和形而上学的现实，这些是所选择的规则应该反映出的。GM可以自由地采用、调整或忽略这些限制，以便更好地将神融入到他们的游戏中。<br>归来的埃及神是强大的，但并未所有埃及神都强大无比，神灵也并非无所不见或无所不知。他们是不朽的，但他们会受伤，甚至会被杀死。死亡不是永恒的:只要他们是有意识的，他们的灵体基本上是完整的，他们可以在物质世界中改造他们的肉体（khat），并从冥界旅行到那里居住。他们也可以在他们的影子（khaibit），他们自己的特殊的肖像(被魔法改变的雕像，绘画，和类似的东西)，与他们建立了精神联系的凡人，以及他们的半神之子的身上显灵。<br>众神被束缚在他们的领域上;他们对每个人的幸福负责，拥有基于领域产生的魔法，并从领域的存在中获得力量。举个例子，赛特是风暴之神，所以他能控制风暴的来去，他能把风暴扔向敌人。只要附近有风暴，他就能从风暴中获得灵气。共享领域的诸神知道其他神在领域内做什么，但不知道这么做的缘由或方式。<br>领域与力量息息相关:力量与控制它的神的灵体联系在一起，如果它受苦，神也受苦。同样，如果它繁荣，神也繁荣，如果它的互补方面繁荣，神也繁荣。这就是为什么“空中之神”荷鲁斯会进入飞机领域:飞在天空的他的飞机越多，他得到的灵气就越多。每当月亮升起时，透特都会获得力量，因为他“使”月亮升起。当他在阴间时，月亮仍然升起，但他无法得知;如果出了什么问题，除了物理之外，什么也救不了世界。<br>神可以可以使用魔法或灵气治愈大多数物理和魔法伤害。然而，他们无法从对他们身体形态造成的精神伤害中恢复过来，比如圣堂武士使用的致命的、汲取灵气的子弹，当它们穿透神灵的魔法和肉体时，这些子弹会撕碎灵体。精神上的伤害会彻底摧毁一个神的存在，但即便如此，如果他们的真名没有被伤害，他们就会化身为凡人，终有一天他们会重获身为神灵记忆。<br>因此，“真名”是最重要的:它是他们个性、神灵身份和力量的钥匙。只要知晓一件事物或一个人的真名，就能够指挥它，从阴间召唤它，赋予它人格或力量，并能够改造或彻底摧毁它。在没有统治者的决定与支持的情况下，以敌对的方式使用另一个神的“真名”，这是一位神犯下的最严重的罪行。这会导致他们自己的真名粉碎和被留在冥界中漂流，无法思考，无法尖叫。理想情况下，一个神自己的真名应该只有他自己知道，但一些神-透特，伊希斯，和仍然失踪的勒内-知道所有神的真名。<br>他们说奥西里斯也知道，但没有神敢问他。<br>较低级的神被知晓他们真名的神从阴间召回。召唤者可以选择混合两个或其中一个神的领域，或者将它们分开。大多数召唤者选择共享他们召唤的神的领域，以获得领域，而不是直接负责它的维护。有些神分享自己的领域，是出于公平，或者是因为他们太忙了，无法处理所有事情。<br>如果众神决定合体成为复合的实体，如三面法老王，他们必须彼此分享他们的真名。他们可能对自己作为一个复合实体所做的事情有不完全的记忆，但他们仍然会记得彼此的真名。从理论上讲，这降低了派系之间发生冲突的可能性，但这还有待检验。<br><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px"><div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px"><b>剧透</b> - &nbsp;<i> </i>: <input type="button" value="顯示" style="width:60px;font-size:10px;margin:0px;padding:0px;" onClick="if (this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display != '') { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = ''; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;this.innerText = ''; this.value = '隐藏'; } else { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'none'; this.innerText = ''; this.value = '显示'; }"></div><div class="alt2" style="margin: 0px; padding: 6px; border: 1px inset;"><div style="display: none;">Whatever game system the GM uses to present the New Kingdom will help flesh out the abilities, powers, and drawbacks of the gods, of course. Here are some general ideas and metaphysical realities about them, which the chosen rules set should reflect. GMs are free to adopt, adapt, or ignore these strictures in order to better fit the gods into their game. <br>The returned Egyptian gods are powerful, but not allpowerful, nor all-seeing or all-knowing. They are ageless and immortal, yet they can be wounded and even killed. Death is not eternal: so long as they are conscious, and their sah is mostly intact, they can reform their khat in the physical world, and travel from the Underworld to inhabit it. They can also manifest in their khaibit, special likenesses of themselves (magically altered statues, paintings, and the like), mortals with whom they have created a spiritual bond, and their demigod children. <br>The gods are bound to their dominions; they are responsible for each one’s well-being and maintenance, have access to magic based on them, and gain power from their existence. For example, Set is the god of storms, so has a hand in their coming and going, and he can throw them at his foes. Whenever a storm is nearby, he can gain sekhem from it. Gods who share dominions know what the other gods are doing within it, though not why or how. <br>Dominions are demanding: The power is tied to the sah of the god that controls it, and if it suffers, so does he. Likewise, if it prospers, so does he, and if a complementary aspect of it prospers, so does he. This is why Horus, god of the air, went into aircraft: The more his planes travel through the sky, the more sekhem he gets. Thoth gains power every time the moon rises, because he “makes” it rise. When he was in the Underworld the moon still rose, but he had no oversight; if something had gone wrong, nothing but physics could have saved the world.<br>Gods can heal from most physical and magical damage, either using magic or sekhem to heal. However, they can’t recover from spiritual damage done to them in their physical forms, such as from the deadly, sekhem-draining bullets the Templars use, which shred the sah as they pierce magic and flesh. Enough spiritual damage destroys a god, but even then there is a chance that, if the ren is undamaged, he will incarnate into mortal flesh, and one day regain his memories. <br>The ren, however, is all-important: It holds they key to their personality, magical identity, and power. To know the ren of a thing or person is to be able to command it, call it from the Underworld, imbue it with personality or powers, and remake or utterly destroy it. To use another god’s ren in a hostile manner, unsupported by a ruler’s decision, is the worst crime any god might commit. It is cause to have their own ren shattered and to be left adrift in the Underworld, mindless and unable to scream. Ideally, a god’s own ren should only be known to him, but some of the gods – Thoth, Isis, and the still-missing Renenet – know them all. <br>They say Osiris knows them all, too, but none dare ask.<br>&nbsp;The lesser gods have been called back from the Underworld by gods who know their ren. The summoner has the option of mingling the dominions of both or either god, or leaving them distinct. Most summoning gods choose to share in the dominions of the god they’re calling up, in order to gain sekhemwhile not being directly responsible for its maintenance. Some share one of their own dominions, out of fairness or because they’re too busy to handle everything. <br>If gods decide to join with one another in a composite entity, such as the tripartite pharaoh, they must share their ren with one another. They may have imperfect memories of what they do as a composite entity, but they will still remember each other’s ren. In theory, this makes conflict between factions less likely, but this has yet to be tested. <br><br><br><br><br><br><br></div></div></div></div>
</div>
</div>
